Vector Embeddings using Qdrant
Objective

The objective of this assignment is to generate vector embeddings from text chunks and store them in a Vector Database (Qdrant). This enables semantic search by representing textual information as numerical vectors instead of plain text.

Introduction

Traditional databases store structured data such as text, numbers, and dates. However, AI applications require storing the semantic meaning of text rather than only the original words.

An embedding model converts each text chunk into a numerical vector. These vectors capture the meaning of the text and are stored in a Vector Database for efficient similarity search.

Dataset

The assignment uses a text file containing 20 individual text chunks.

Each line in the file represents one chunk of text that is converted into a vector embedding.

Embedding Generation

The Sentence Transformer model all-MiniLM-L6-v2 is used to convert every text chunk into a vector representation.

Each generated embedding contains 384 numerical values, representing the semantic features of the text.

These vectors are generated automatically by the embedding model.

Vector Database

Qdrant is used as the Vector Database.

A collection named legal_chunks is created to store all generated embeddings.

Each stored record contains:

Unique ID
Vector Embedding
Original Text (Payload)

The payload preserves the original text while the vector enables semantic searching.

Workflow

The complete workflow consists of the following steps:

Read text chunks.
Generate embeddings using Sentence Transformers.
Connect to the Qdrant server.
Create a collection.
Store vectors with their payload.
Verify successful storage using the Qdrant Dashboard.
Benefits
Enables semantic search.
Supports AI-based document retrieval.
Stores the meaning of text instead of exact keywords.
Efficient retrieval of similar documents.
Suitable for Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) systems.